You and I are part of long, self-reinforcing cycles of caring, safety, etc. The fundamental problem with AI is it has no self-reinforcing cycles of goodness. It takes a lot of effort to raise a child (parent's love, etc.) and maintain a society so that human cycles can be repeated. But it’s the opposite with AI. There is competition for patents and financial rewards so programmers test something in the lab and the AI is thrown out to the world when it is refined enough to solve some problem (e.g., earning income from chatGPT).  We should expect very good but also very bad outcomes from AI because we are not growing slowly as a society with AI. Maybe if it took 40 years between SMRTYpants 1.0, 2.0 and 3.0 we'd be ok but the AI iterations are only a few years apart.

One of the biggest underappreciated hurdles I suspect AI will face is in actually integrating into regular businesses. Using ChatGPT on its own is one thing, but to actually replace most knowledge work would require the AI to have access to, be able to comprehend and helpfully interpret novel company data, usually spread over a variety of mediums (e.g. emails, databases, pdfs...etc.) and not always well organised, not to mention understand subtext from meetings...etc. There is a lot of architectural engineering that would have to go into that in most companies looking to seriously adopt AI, not to mention companies will have to be certain it's secure. 

Until that actually happens, I suspect actual productivity gains in most jobs from AI will be marginal - documents will be quicker to read and write, spreadsheets will be autofilled, coding bugs will be identified...etc.

The future is a personal "ChatGPT" assistant for each and every person. This AI assistant will integrate into every digital device a person uses (computers, smart phones, gaming systems, EV cars, etc.). The AI assistant will learn everything it can about you and tailor your digital experience accordingly. This will further place people into their individual reality bubbles. It will also make it extremely easy to customize propaganda for each person to maximize results. A few generations down the line and those future people will fully trust that their AI assistant is always giving them 100% accurate information. Even now, the screens in our lives are warping our perception of reality. As AI tools are incorporated and become more and more trusted, this separation from the real world will dramatically increase. Once you've severed people's connection to reality, they become absurdly easy to manipulate. 

This is the thing Sci-Fi literature and films always get wrong. The "AI" will not ruin humans by physically attacking them. The AI will ruin humans by removing all personal responsibility from their lives and turning them into useless consumers. AI dependent humans of the future will be incapable of critical thinking and incapable of doing any task for themselves in the real world.

The dilemma of AI goes like this: the usual fantasy of a human-like robot is something that outdoes 'human-ness' by being more creative, intelligent etc than the usual human. This will never exist because humans are autonomous and can make decisions for themselves. No one wants to create a robot that will do what it wants, rather than obey its creator. For example, who wants a ChatGPT that when you ask it for a treatise on ancient history gives you a story about fairies because that's what the ChatGPT is more interested in at the moment. AI is about improved tools, there will never be a bot that is an improved human.

Chomsky has spoken at length about this exact thing. Having worked at MIT for nearly half a century, he's seen first hand how we've been "one year away" for decades. AI also presupposes the idea that the mind exists in the brain, and not vice versa - an assumption which is not held by all fields of STEM, and definitely not all fields of study. 

I work with ChatGPT a lot, and while super interesting and promising, it's so far from being "intelligent". It's very good at giving correct answers, but we've been able to do stuff like this since the mid 1980s. AI has just replaced crypto as the "hot" investment after the FTX/SBF debacle imo. There is value to the tech, but it's being blown so far out of proportion it's insane.

In applications without intentionality Artificial Intelligence (AI) is an answer looking for a problem with the hope of getting lucky. This is strikingly evident in an AI image creation where a human hand is involved. How often do these images misrepresent a normal hand? How basic is the human inference to know what the typical human hand is, even in various positions? AI such as ChatGPT may provide a capable insight into language interpretation and generation, but I feel it will lack the nuance of artistry that is apparent like when you hear a concerto played a string quartet when using high-end Stradivarius instruments vs. string instruments purchased off of Ali Express.  We absorb content into our senses and mind via analog inputs. Digital renditions have become very good at the mimicry of each instance, but that digital AI experience still lacks the subtleness of a chord vibrato or a hint of shadow that still stirs emotions in the human experience.

Having spent several hours with ChatGPT, I've noticed that even though it is the frontrunner in the public eye, it is not without serious limitations. For the one, many of the responses to even basic questions can be wildly inaccurate. I asked it to describe Sandra Bullock, and evidently Ms. Bullock has short, blonde curls. Second, the developers' editorial bias has a bearing on almost everything you might ask of the AI.

A philosopher - someone paid to think - arguing that computers aren't "thinking" is like a production line worker arguing that robots aren't welding - the cars they're no-longer paid to weld...

All human interaction comes down to "learn what reply is best in this situation" and that's all AI is doing - it's learning the most appropriate responses to information it's given - be that the tags to create an image or the data which might contain credit-card fraud or whatever...  We then take that response and interpret it - we "like" the picture or we find the patterns in the credit card data correspond to a particular type of fraud and so rely on that system or whatever...

The fact that ChatGPT doesn't just respond to/in human language but also to computer languages or even protocols which create images or documents demonstrates this pretty well.

It's natural for humans to assume what we do is special and hard-to-replicate but outside of our own personal experience (which is all that matters most of the time) it really isn't

How does it learn? Would it be able to watch traffic on the internet, news broadcasts, etc... and be able to synthesize and absorb what it observes?
Given that it is a software program (albeit a very large and complex one) would multiple instances of it, running on different hosts be able to communicate with each other? I'm thinking of the Go playing program that recently beat the world champion. After absorbing historical games played by humans,  it played copies of itself - this resulted in winning strategies not understood by even masters of the game.
What kind of goals would it have?  Humans have basic goals ingrained - to eat, get laid, seek status or power, etc... Does the program have any basic underlying goals to direct its behavior?

The possibility of ChatGPT or any other artificial intelligence becoming conscious is a topic of much debate and speculation.
 
On one hand, some argue that consciousness is simply a result of complex computations taking place in the brain, and as AI becomes more advanced, it could potentially reach a level of complexity where consciousness arises as a byproduct. This perspective is known as the computational theory of mind.
 
On the other hand, there are those who argue that consciousness is something fundamentally different from computation, and that it is unlikely that a machine could ever truly be conscious. This perspective is known as the non-computational theory of mind.
 
One issue with the idea of AI becoming conscious is that we currently do not have a clear understanding of what consciousness is and how it arises. Without this understanding, it is difficult to say whether or not it is possible for AI to become conscious.
 
Another issue is that current AI systems, such as ChatGPT, are not designed to be conscious. They are designed to perform specific tasks, such as natural language processing, and do not have the ability to experience subjective feelings or self-awareness.
 
In conclusion, the possibility of ChatGPT or any other AI becoming conscious is a complex and highly debated topic. While some argue that it is possible for machines to become conscious, others believe that consciousness is a fundamentally non-computational phenomenon that cannot be replicated in a machine. Additionally, current AI systems are not designed to be conscious, and we still have much to learn about the nature of consciousness and how it arises. -ChatGPT

Well, that analogy with child learning to speak and become more sentient in the process is both deep and incorrect. Communication is very important part of our consciousness, but it's not the only part. Significant part of our perceived "psyche" is so called narrator (or ego) and it's all language, but there are much more layers than just narrator. And so, back to our child - he or she uses (and trains) all those layers including bodily sensations and control, emotions in addition to speech/narrator to become sentient. Or in other words child not just speak, child also act and actively uses what he/she learns and that's huge part of learning process. ChatGPT has no body, no ways neither to perceive the world nor manipulate/mange it. So, GPT (no matter the version) is not enough to become sentient, but combined with other AIs to a complex and interdependent system like our brain (plus body) it might be a part of AGI.

It has highly limited options to output something - it can only write text and not use a keyboard for example. It predicts some values that than in another place get transformed into words and printed on your screen

It only gives an output after receiving an input - there is no internal thinking that would cause it to develop on its own and this also means it won’t start taking actions on its own.

Related to this point, it got designed to fulfill an objective and is because of the point above not able to set its own objectives and pursuing them. 

It also doesn’t have access to real time information. It learned something once and everything that happened after that it won’t be able to understand. Like with Chatgpt currently which is limited to knowledge until the end of 2021.

ChatGPT is pretty impressive. Or at least it seems that way now. I predict that before this year is out, it will seem quaintly primitive. 
This area is advancing fast and it's not just the models but also the hardware that's advancing rapidly. The ML computers being built this year have actual synapse analogues - not binary representations, running on silicon. These (neuromorphic) ML processors use memristors that function as both processor and memory. They don't have a clock but are spiking neural networks, like an organic brain. They are not limited to 1s and 0s but are analogue. Some will use bayesian inference to provide more accurate results from noisy, imperfect data. They will be many times faster, much more accurate and use a fraction of the resources, including energy. 
The field of ML and AGI will look very different by the end of this year to how it looks today.

ChatGPT has a very heavy bias towards affirmative responses. For example, if you ask it a basic programming question like "In the C programming language, does strlen count the null terminator?" It will tell you that it does count the null terminator, even though that is false. However, if you word the question like "In the C programming language, strlen doesn't count the null terminator, does it?", it will tell you that you are correct and that it does not count the null terminator. I'm assuming this type of bias is inherent in the training data, but it is still something that OpenAI needs to examine and try to mitigate. ChatGPT bends over backwards to agree with you and confirm whatever you are asking about, as long as you don't trip one of it's many content filters. This is a HUGE problem and will lead to an increase in confirmation bias among the masses if it is not resolved. Another issue is that it will rarely give you a response along the lines of "I don't know" and it will give you completely false information in an attempt to answer a question that it doesn't have sufficient data on.

Interesting ChatGPT response... skews what an anagram is... why is not ´Satoshi Nakamoto´ an anagram of ´I am not ok as a host´? While it is true that both "Satoshi Nakamoto" and "I am not OK as a host" contain the same set of letters, the latter is not an anagram of the former because not all of the letters are used in the same frequency or order.
For example, the letters "h", "s", and "t" appear twice in "Satoshi Nakamoto", but only once in "I am not OK as a host". Similarly, the letters "m" and "k" appear twice in "I am not OK as a host", but are not present in "Satoshi Nakamoto". 
To form an anagram, all of the letters from the original word or phrase must be used exactly once (although additional letters can also be added, if desired). In the case of "Satoshi Nakamoto", there are many possible anagrams that can be formed using all of the letters, such as "Aim to stash a nook" or "Oh, a tsunami took a".

4:11 “…and like a banana refers to the idea that the flies are drawn to the banana just as time flies by quickly.”
Actually, that doesn’t make any sense and points up how ChatGPT emulates human speech while not really being right in some commonsense way. There’s no “just as” implied with the two phrases. They’re used together only because in English x flies like a y gives rise to two entirely different grammatical patterns and one test is whether ChatGPT can differentiate between the two of them.

Out of curiosity, I gave ChatGPT the phrase Fruit flies like an arrow. Here’s what it said, in part:

One possible interpretation is that “fruit flies” refers to small insects that are attracted to fruits and that they move quickly and directly, like an arrow. In this sense, the phrase could be seen as a statement about the behavior of fruit flies. 
 
Another possible interpretation is that “fruit” is being used as a verb, and “flies” is being used as a noun, with “like an arrow” providing a comparison.

The first “possible interpretation” is simply wrong—it’s as if it’s interpreting the phrase Fruit flies fly like an arrow. The second is possible but it’s exceedingly unlikely that “fruit” is being used as a verb. Again, ChatGPT is emulating human speech but what it says really makes no sense.

ChatGPT is amazing but I've run across simple cases where it's wrong due to contradiction even with simple high school level physics questions. 
Example:
Prompt "A ball falls from a height of 5 meters. Ignoring wind resistance, is the potential energy before it starts falling equal to the kinetic energy when it hits the ground."

Reponse: "No, the potential energy before it starts falling is not equal to the kinetic energy when it hits the ground. Potential energy is converted to kinetic energy as the ball falls. The formula for potential energy is mgh (mass x gravitational acceleration x height), while the formula for kinetic energy is 1/2mv^2 (mass x velocity squared). The potential energy will be equal to kinetic energy only when it reach the ground and come to rest."

The response contradicts itself.
"No, the potential energy before it starts falling is not equal to the kinetic energy when it hits the ground"
"The potential energy will be equal to kinetic energy only when it reach the ground and come to rest"

Also, it makes no sense to talk about kinetic energy when something is "at rest". When something is "at rest" it has no kinetic energy.  I would grade the answer as 5 out of 10 were I to get this answer from a student.

Additionally, notice the strange grammar error ( "......only when it reach the ground and come to rest").

When questioned about the validity of it's response, however, it did correct itself with the following:
"You are correct, my previous statement was incorrect. I apologize for the confusion. The total mechanical energy of the system, which is the sum of the potential energy and kinetic energy, is conserved as the ball falls. The potential energy is converted to kinetic energy as the ball falls. At the moment the ball is dropped, the potential energy is at its maximum and the kinetic energy is zero, while at the moment it hits the ground the potential energy is zero, and the kinetic energy is at its maximum. The total energy before and after the fall is the same."

The weirdest thing I've found messing around with it, is sometimes it will straight up tell you it doesn't have data to answer a question, but other times it will actually make "educated guesses" that are actually wrong. It's literally bullshitting you. Making things up that it "thinks" are probably correct, based on inferences from available information. An easy way to produce this is to ask it what the premise of some obscure fictional novel is. It doesn't actually have access to the novel itself, really just metadata like the title, genre, sub-genre, author, date of publication, etc. and maybe some things like reviews or summaries. It can use those things to infer what the premise is, based on themes and tropes common to that genre and time period, and maybe the author if that kind of data is available. The thing is, if the novel in question actually breaks from those trends, it doesn't know it. So it gives you a summary that sounds like it makes sense based on the title and the genre and whatnot, but for that particular novel it might be completely off base. 

The other interesting part of ChatGPT is how good it is at coding. I'd say its actually better at that than "normal" conversation. Ask it how to accomplish some task in just about any programming language, and it will give you detailed instructions along with good sample code where you usually just need to substitute some variable names.

6 ÷ 2 (3)
Next, we evaluate the expression inside the parentheses:
6 ÷ 2 (3)
becomes:

6 ÷ 6 = 1

As a university researcher in VR and computer visualization, Dall-E2 will certainly open up exciting new opportunities.  But for someone who has taught at the college level for over 40 years, I also know that in the hands of my students,  AI applications like Dall-E2 and Chapt GPT will be used to reduce the time spent on the act of producing a work of art or writing an essay.  Each term I grade hundreds of essays.  How will I know if the work they submit was the product of AI?  Though ChatGPT creates the same output from the same input terms. However, by varying the input terms slightly you can produce a different essay. My experimentation with ChatGPT has produced essays that are better written than 90% of what is submitted during the term.  For those students in the visual arts, Dall-E2 can create numerous permutations from a single set of keywords.  Most of the experiments have produced works of art that I know my students could never create. For those college students who look for the easy way out, the use of these tools will result in little learning over their tenure in college. It is true that in the past students plagiarized the work of others. However, these tools will just make it even more difficult for the instructor to know which essay or work of art is the product of actual learning or that of an AI bot.

There is a way you can knead that watery semolina dough, called the coil fold method. When you start you're certain it will never work, but after a lot of folding with multiple rests in between, it does. The issue is that semola/semolina, while high in protein generally, is low in the specific kinds of protein that form gluten, so you have to really work (or give a longer time to) the gluten-producing proteins it does have. You'll never get anything close to traditional bread dough, but you'll eventually get to something recognizable as dough.

I think the biggest miss with ChatGPT is that it doesn't truly mimic human behavior. People often leave details out when they initially ask questions and the bot didn't ask any follow up questions, like preferences, disorders, allergies, what does your average day look like. These sorts of questions are ones that I feel a general dietician would ask someone before spitting out a full meal plan.

ChatGPT’s training data cutoff was 2021 so it doesn’t have information that occurred after that year if that sheds some light on its recommendations. Really fun video I love all the peanutbutter reccs it made

I think if you had given it much more information around your preferences and dietary needs (at least macro percentages) it would have given you a much better plan. ChatGPT was literally only given your age, weight, and need to maintain. That’s it. Just a thought for the next trial run.

I told ChatGPT that I am a vegetarian who is allergic to peanuts and tree nuts and have a very low cooking skill, and that I am trying to lose a large amount of weight. I asked it to tell me what to eat for a day, and it did a pretty good job.

I tried chatgpt with the prompt "balanced meal plan for 28 years old female, high protein, 1800 calories, Bengali cuisine" and the result was quite satisfactory. And writing prompts are becoming a skill nowadays to get better results from AI and you can edit your prompt as well. So I think your point about protein and culture were kinda not accurate, as one could simply clearer prompts to get better results. My result had fish for lunch and chicken for dinner and other protein sources like lentil, nuts,etc.
